{{Quote|Contrary to what some nose-in-the-air Core Worlder'll tell you, I'm not pointing at Coruscant.|Crix Q5 Baobab, regarding the Galactic Center|<ref name="Atlas" />}}
The '''Galactic Center''' was a supermassive [[Black hole/Legends|black hole]] that existed at the center of [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] within the [[Deep Core/Legends|Deep Core]]. Like other black holes, it was identified as a [[Star/Legends|star]] of class P. Its mass was estimated to be four million stellar masses, and all four hundred billion stars in the [[Galaxy/Legends|galaxy]] revolved around it. [[Antimatter]], [[Gas/Legends|gas]], and approximately thirty million densely packed stars closely surrounded the Galactic Center, though the latter was not within its immediate vicinity. While no living [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] had ever witnessed the Galactic Center firsthand, [[Probe droid/Legends|probe droids]] had been sent to observe it and confirmed its existence. Despite its actual location to the northeast of the Galactic Center on the galactic plane, the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] was also commonly referred to as the center of the galaxy.

==Description==
{{Quote|This is a black hole&mdash;one that weighs as much as four million suns.|Crix Q5 Baobab|<ref name="Atlas" />}}
[[File:Coruscant-EotE.jpg|thumb|240px|left|Coruscant was often figuratively referred to as the center of the galaxy.]]
A supermassive [[Black hole/Legends|black hole]] of [[Star/Legends|stellar]] class P, the Galactic Center was situated at the very center of [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]] in the [[Deep Core/Legends|Deep Core]] and was the object around which all<ref name="Atlas" /> four hundred billion<ref name="NumOfStars" /> stars of the [[Galaxy/Legends|galaxy]] [[Orbit/Legends|orbited]]. The immediate area around the black hole was devoid of stars, however, and instead had large amounts of [[Gas/Legends|gas]] spiraling into it.<ref name="Atlas" /> The Galactic Center's immediate vicinity also contained [[antimatter]],<ref name="FactFile7">{{FactFile|7|PLA 1-6|Planets of the Core Worlds}}</ref> while there were approximately thirty billion<ref name="Atlas" /> densely packed<ref name="FactFile7" /> stars further out in the Deep Core. Its mass was estimated to be the equivalent to that of four million stars.<ref name="Atlas" />

As a result of its proximity to the Galactic Center,<ref name="Darksaber">[[Darksaber (novel)|''Darksaber'']]</ref> the [[Planet/Legends|planet]]<ref name="Atlas" /> [[Khomm/Legends|Khomm's]] [[Moon/Legends|moonless]] [[Atmosphere/Legends|sky]] was filled with numerous bright stars.<ref name="Darksaber" /> Despite the Galactic Center being the true center-point of the galaxy, the planet [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]] was frequently referred to as the galactic center<ref name="Atlas" /> and was even known as the center of the [[Universe/Legends|universe]].<ref name="EAWGuide">[[Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption Expansion: Prima Official Game Guide|''Star Wars: Empire at War: Forces of Corruption Expansion'': Prima Official Game Guide]]</ref> The planet featured a [[Spaceport/Legends|spaceport]] known as the [[Galactic Center Spaceport]],<ref name="Apocalypse">''[[Fate of the Jedi: Apocalypse]]''</ref> and the [[Galactic Senate Medcenter/Legends|Galactic Senate Medcenter]]&mdash;also on Coruscant&mdash;was sometimes referred to as the Galactic Center Medcenter.<ref name="CSWEMedcenter">{{CSWECite|I|308|Galactic Center Medcenter}}</ref> Coruscant had the XYZ-format [[Galactic coordinates/Legends|galactic coordinates]] of 0,0,0&mdash;despite its position slightly northwest and above the plane of ecliptic with respect to the true Galactic Center. This discrepancy frustrated [[Astrocartography|astrocartographers]] for [[Millennium/Legends|millennia]].<ref name="Atlas" />

==History==
===Before civil war===
{{Quote|From what I'd heard from spice pirates and deep-space pilots, it sounded like the exact opposite of Tatooine. Tatooine was a forgotten wasteland on the Outer Rim. Coruscant was the center of the galaxy.|Anakin Skywalker's journal, regarding Coruscant|<ref name="AnakinJournal">''[[Star Wars Journal: Anakin Skywalker]]''</ref>}}
[[File:DarthBane-TEA.jpg|thumb|220px|Darth Bane once pondered a fate of endlessly orbiting the Galactic Center.]]
Around [[995 BBY]],<ref name="BaneDate">The section of ''[[Darth Bane: Rule of Two]]'' that included [[Darth Bane/Legends|Darth Bane's]] research for creating a [[Sith holocron/Legends|Sith holocron]] occurs approximately fifteen [[Standard year/Legends|years]] after the founding of the [[Brotherhood of Darkness/Legends|Brotherhood of Darkness]], which ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]'' dates to [[1010 BBY]]. As such, the events of that section must have occurred around [[995 BBY]].</ref> the [[Dark Lord of the Sith/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Darth Bane/Legends|Darth Bane]] noted that his [[Infiltrator-series long-range fighter|''Infiltrator''-series long-range fighter]] [[Mystic (starfighter)|''Mystic'']] would become his "coffin" floating around the Galactic Center if his [[Hyperspace/Legends|hyperspace]] journey into the Deep Core failed.<ref name="RuleOfTwo">''[[Darth Bane: Rule of Two]]''</ref> In [[32 BBY/Legends|32 BBY]],<ref name="ReadersCompAnakin">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' places the events of [[Star Wars Journal: Anakin Skywalker|''Star Wars Episode I Journal: Anakin Skywalker'']] in [[32 BBY/Legends|32 BBY]].</ref> the [[Youngling/Legends|youngling]] [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] referred to Coruscant as the center of the galaxy in his [[Anakin Skywalker's journal|journal]].<ref name="AnakinJournal" />

At some point, the existence of the Galactic Center was confirmed through the use of [[Probe droid/Legends|probe droids]], though it was never observed by any [[Sentience/Legends|sentient]] beings firsthand. During a class held at the [[Baobab Merchant Marine Academy]] in the [[Imperial Era/Legends|Imperial Period]], [[Instructor/Legends|Instructor]] [[Crix Q5 Baobab]] once lectured their students on the Galactic Center, informing them of its mass, status as the galaxy's center, and its discovery by probe [[Droid/Legends|droids]]. Baobab also remarked that an individual from the [[Core Worlds/Legends|Core Worlds]] might falsely claim that the galaxy revolved around the planet Coruscant instead of the Galactic Center.<ref name="Atlas" />

===The Galactic Empire===
{{Quote|I can hardly believe it&hellip; where did the time go?''"<br />"''Where time always goes. There's a giant black hole in the center of the galaxy, and it just sucks it right up.|Bria Tharen and Lando Calrissian|<ref name="RebelDawn">''[[Rebel Dawn]]''</ref>}}
[[Snillik]] was a thick [[Liqueur/Legends|liqueur]] that was produced near the Galactic Center<ref name="FlamewindofOseon">''[[Lando Calrissian and the Flamewind of Oseon]]''</ref> by [[2 BBY/Legends|2 BBY]].<ref name="ReadersCompFlamewind">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' places the events of [[Star Wars: The Lando Calrissian Adventures|''The Lando Calrissian Adventures'']], which includes ''[[Lando Calrissian and the Mindharp of Sharu]]'' and ''[[Lando Calrissian and the Flamewind of Oseon]]'', to between [[3 BBY/Legends|3 BBY]] and [[2 BBY/Legends|2 BBY]].</ref> After an artifact of early [[Realspace/Legends|spaceflight]] collided with the [[YT-1300 light freighter/Legends|light freighter]] [[Millennium Falcon/Legends|''Millennium Falcon'']] in the orbit of the planet [[Rafa V]]<ref name="Mindharp">''[[Lando Calrissian and the Mindharp of Sharu]]''</ref> at some point between [[3 BBY/Legends|3 BBY]] and 2 [[Galactic Standard Calendar|BBY]],<ref name="ReadersCompFlamewind" /> the [[Freighter/Legends|freighter's]] [[Captain/Legends|captain]], the [[Gambler/Legends|gambler]] [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando Calrissian]], made an exclamation with reference to the Galactic Center.<ref name="Mindharp" />

In [[1 BBY/Legends|1 BBY]], [[Doctor/Legends|Doctor]] [[Insmot Bowen]] speculated that the [[Celestial/Legends|Celestials]]<ref name="GuidetoWarfareAuthorsCut">{{SW|url=news/star-wars-the-essential-guide-to-warfare-authors-cut-the-celestials|text=''Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare'' Author's Cut &mdash; The Celestials|int=Star Wars: The Essential Guide to Warfare Author's Cut}}</ref>&mdash;[[Immortality/Legends|immortal]] entities of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]<ref name="Apoc">''[[Fate of the Jedi: Apocalypse]]''</ref>&mdash;created the galaxy's [[circumferential hyperspace barrier]] by manipulating energy drawn from the Galactic Center.<ref name="GuidetoWarfareAuthorsCut" /> Around [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]],<ref name="RebelDawnTimeline">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' establishes that the events of ''[[Rebel Dawn]]'' take place from [[2 BBY/Legends|2 BBY]] to [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]]. ''The Essential Reader's Companion'' also establishes that the events of ''[[The Paradise Snare]]'' take place around [[10 BBY/Legends|10 BBY]], which includes the first meeting between [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and [[Bria Tharen]]. In ''Rebel Dawn'', Tharen mentions it has been ten [[Standard year/Legends|years]] since she and Solo met in the same conversation [[Lando Calrissian/Legends|Lando Calrissian]] mentions the Galactic Center. As such, that conversation must have occurred around 0 [[Galactic Standard Calendar|BBY]].</ref> Calrissian quipped to the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] operative [[Bria Tharen]] that the black hole consumed [[Time/Legends|time]] itself.<ref name="RebelDawn" /> After the [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler]] [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]], who by then had become captain of the ''Millennium Falcon'', claimed that the [[Starship/Legends|starship]] could make point five factors beyond [[Lightspeed/Legends|lightspeed]] when [[Farmer/Legends|farmhand]] [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] first saw the vessel<ref name="ANHNovel">[[Star Wars: A New Hope (novelization)|''Star Wars: A New Hope'' novelization]]</ref> in 0 BBY,<ref name="ANHdate">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]'' dates the first meeting between [[Han Solo/Legends|Han Solo]] and [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] to [[0 BBY/Legends|0 BBY]].</ref> Skywalker thought to himself that Solo was possibly the biggest liar "on that side of the Galactic Center."<ref name="ANHNovel" />

====After the Empire====
{{Quote|Muur is playing mind games with the people here&mdash;trying to play mind games with ''me''&mdash;and it is going to stop.''"<br />"Or? ''Threats usually come with an ''or'', Master Skywalker.''"<br />"Or ''I stuff you and that trinket into a rocket and send you into a black hole at the center of the Deep Core.|Cade Skywalker and Celeste Morne|<ref name="Legacy29">[[Legacy (2006) 29|''Legacy'' (2006) 29]]</ref>}}
[[File:CadeSkywalkerJettison.png|thumb|left|215px|Cade Skywalker threatens to jettison Celeste Morne into the Galactic Center.]]
Following its presumed destruction during the [[Battle of the Maw]]<ref name="Champions">''[[Champions of the Force]]''</ref> in [[11 ABY/Legends|11 ABY]],<ref name="ReadersCompChampions">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' places the events of ''[[Champions of the Force]]'' in [[11 ABY/Legends|11 ABY]].</ref> the [[Imperial I-class Star Destroyer/Legends|''Imperial I''-class Star Destroyer]] ''[[Gorgon]]'' retreated toward the bright area of the galaxy surrounding the Galactic Center&mdash;bound for the Deep Core&mdash;to join [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperial]] forces based there.<ref name="Champions" /> The [[Yuuzhan Vong War|invasion]] of the galaxy by the [[Yuuzhan Vong galaxy|extra-galactic]] [[Yuuzhan Vong]] [[Species/Legends|species]] took a sharp turn in course for the Galactic Center in [[26 ABY/Legends|26 ABY]] when their [[Yuuzhan Vong empire|forces]] [[Battle of Duro (Yuuzhan Vong War)|set their sights]] on the planet [[Duro/Legends|Duro]].<ref name="NEC">''[[The New Essential Chronology]]''</ref> At some point between [[35 ABY/Legends|35 ABY]] and [[36 ABY]],<ref name="ReadersCompSwarm">''[[The Essential Reader's Companion]]'' places the events of ''[[Star Wars: The Dark Nest Trilogy]]'', which includes [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker's]] [[Lightsaber duel/Legends|duel]] with [[Raynar Thul]] in ''[[Dark Nest III: The Swarm War]]'' to between [[35 ABY/Legends|35 ABY]] and [[36 ABY]].</ref> Luke Skywalker fought in a [[Lightsaber duel/Legends|duel]] with [[Raynar Thul|UnuThul]], the leader of [[the Colony]]&mdash;an organization of the sentient [[Insectoid/Legends|insectoid]] [[Killik/Legends|Killik]] species. Skywalker, by then a [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] [[Grand Master/Legends|Grand Master]], [[Force power/Legends|used]] the Force during the duel to render himself nearly immovable, pondering the idea that not even the Galactic Center could falter him.<ref name="SwarmWar">''[[Dark Nest III: The Swarm War]]''</ref> The Galactic Center and its role and significance in history were recorded in a [[The New Essential Chronology (in-universe)|chronicle]] of [[Timeline of galactic history/Legends|galactic history]] written by the [[Historical Council]] of the [[Galactic Federation of Free Alliances|Galactic Alliance]] and published in 36 ABY.<ref name="NEC" />

Around [[137 ABY]], [[Bounty hunter/Legends|bounty hunter]] [[Cade Skywalker]] threatened to jettison [[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Celeste Morne]] into the Galactic Center if [[Sith Lord/Legends|Sith Lord]] [[Karness Muur]]&mdash;who was exerting his will through a [[Muur Talisman|talisman]] on Morne's neck&mdash;did not stop mentally toying with the people present in an [[Darth Krayt's Galactic Empire|Imperial]] stronghold on<ref name="Legacy29" /> the planet<ref name="Legacy28">[[Legacy (2006) 28|''Legacy'' (2006) 28]]</ref> [[Had Abbadon]].<ref name="Legacy29" />

==Behind the scenes==
The Galactic Center was first mentioned in [[Alan Dean Foster]]'s [[1976]] [[Star Wars: A New Hope (novelization)|novelization]] of<ref name="ANHNovel" /> the [[1977]] [[original trilogy]] film, [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'': Episode IV ''A New Hope'']].<ref name="ANH">{{Film|IV}}</ref> The [[2009]] reference book ''[[The Essential Atlas]]'' placed the Galactic Center on the border between grid squares K-11 and L-11.<ref name="Atlas" />

